43:15.750 --> 43:16.750
He is from the colonies.

43:17.291 --> 43:19.558
Your Majesty, his native
tongue is all he understands.

43:26.708 --> 43:29.058
The gates of hell are open night and day.

43:30.208 --> 43:35.766
Smooth is the descent and easiest away.

43:40.333 --> 43:48.333
But to come back from hell
and view the cheerful skies in this,

43:48.666 --> 43:51.184
the task and mighty labor lies.

43:51.208 --> 43:57.350
[PANTING]

43:59.208 --> 44:00.208
Virgil, your Majesty.

44:01.541 --> 44:02.541
Poetry!

44:03.333 --> 44:04.933
[LAUGHTER]

44:05.583 --> 44:07.016
Very clever, my goodness.

44:07.166 --> 44:08.166
Thank you.

44:09.500 --> 44:11.850
I've grown so
bored, but you surprised me.

44:12.375 --> 44:15.101
To amuse you is my only wish.

44:15.125 --> 44:16.558
We are amused. We are amused.

44:18.916 --> 44:19.916
We are amused.

44:21.500 --> 44:26.850
And we all look forward to
seeing your poet perform in the arena.

44:27.375 --> 44:29.725
As do I, your Majesties.

44:30.875 --> 44:31.875
Thank you.

44:32.958 --> 44:35.308
Vigo, come with me.

44:47.208 --> 44:51.183
[PANTING]

44:54.208 --> 44:56.266
You fought well
today, but you were lucky too.

44:59.291 --> 45:00.683
The lines you recited.

45:01.833 --> 45:03.725
You didn't learn
that in Africa. I know that.

45:05.250 --> 45:06.808
A good verse travels far.

45:08.000 --> 45:09.000
Who taught you poetry?

45:09.708 --> 45:11.183
A captioned Roman officer.

45:12.458 --> 45:16.308
I was posted guard over him, and
he used to tell us tales to pass the time.

45:17.958 --> 45:19.183
And what became of this prison?

45:19.458 --> 45:20.558
How we ate him.

45:22.166 --> 45:23.391
As barbarians do.

45:23.500 --> 45:24.975
As barbarians do.

45:25.750 --> 45:26.750
And where were you born?

45:27.833 --> 45:31.600
Why does my past matter if it is
my future to die for you in the arena?

45:38.208 --> 45:41.266
Tell me what you survive for Roman money.

45:42.208 --> 45:48.058
A gladiator can buy his own freedom.

45:49.750 --> 45:50.750
His liberty.

45:52.583 --> 45:53.583
The Roman dream.

45:54.541 --> 45:58.600
The slave dreams not of
freedom, but of a slave to call his own.

45:59.833 --> 46:00.833
Cicero.

46:02.416 --> 46:04.058
Is that what you
were raised on, Maccrelas?

46:05.583 --> 46:07.266
What did you have to do for Roman money?

46:08.208 --> 46:11.225
You promised me a head.

46:12.083 --> 46:13.308
Earn your keep and
you can have anyone's head.

46:39.125 --> 46:47.791
Father, protect us and guide us.

46:57.375 --> 46:58.375
Senators.

46:59.375 --> 47:00.375
My lady.

47:01.208 --> 47:09.208
I wish we were meeting in better times.

47:11.041 --> 47:12.266
Better times will come.

47:14.000 --> 47:15.850
And why are we here?

47:16.666 --> 47:17.891
To take back the city.

47:20.333 --> 47:24.433
And restore Rome to where she should be.

47:25.375 --> 47:26.516
An exciting venture.

47:27.166 --> 47:28.808
When? On the final day of the games.
When? On the final day of the games. When?

47:29.416 --> 47:30.725
On the final day of the games.

47:31.916 --> 47:33.725
My army waits for my command at Ostia.

47:34.833 --> 47:36.766
Five thousand soldiers loyal to me.

47:39.083 --> 47:43.559
We'll enter Rome and then the
Colosseum where they will arrest the emperors for

47:43.583 --> 47:46.683
their crimes against
the Senate and their people.

47:48.708 --> 47:52.516
This plan is ambitious and risky.

47:53.666 --> 47:56.184
Rome will be yours
to administer and to...

47:56.208 --> 48:00.558
Marcus Aurelius talked of
restoring power to the Senate.

48:01.041 --> 48:04.058
But that was a
generation ago. Much has changed.

48:05.458 --> 48:08.100
The people have not seen hope.

48:09.541 --> 48:10.725
For many years.

48:10.875 --> 48:11.875
But with time.

48:13.375 --> 48:14.375
And guidance.

48:15.416 --> 48:19.016
Lucilla, you are the
daughter of Marcus Aurelius.

48:19.375 --> 48:20.975
He had my loyalty.

48:23.750 --> 48:24.850
And so do you.

48:27.875 --> 48:28.891
Senator Thraxx.

48:31.041 --> 48:33.725
Politics follows power, my lady.

48:35.375 --> 48:37.808
Take back what is rightfully yours.

48:39.208 --> 48:41.683
And the Senate will support you.

48:42.541 --> 48:43.541
Thank you.

49:02.333 --> 49:09.808
When I was told of this
place, you never mentioned the stink.

49:12.208 --> 49:13.308
That would be Hanos.

49:17.208 --> 49:19.891
Well, you'll have
to put up with me as I am.

49:22.333 --> 49:27.516
And what's that up there? A wolf?

49:29.833 --> 49:31.850
The twins there, they were outcasts.

49:33.375 --> 49:34.516
Left in the hills to die.

49:36.708 --> 49:39.433
That wolf found them.
She suckled them on her milk.

49:41.583 --> 49:43.391
Raised by an
animal that's in their blood.

49:44.500 --> 49:45.500
How do you know this place?

49:47.916 --> 49:49.308
I know the chaos they brought.

49:51.041 --> 49:53.100
This city infects everything it touches.

49:54.041 --> 49:55.683
I never dreamt it would be so big.

49:56.208 --> 49:59.308
Don't fall for it. This city is diseased.

50:40.541 --> 50:53.208
The No way!

51:11.875 --> 51:12.875
Ah!

51:15.250 --> 51:19.558
Stare speakers and happy honeyfuckers.

51:20.291 --> 51:22.351
Ah, the barbarian.

51:22.375 --> 51:23.226
I haven't forgotten.

51:23.250 --> 51:23.851
I always repay my debts.

51:23.875 --> 51:25.517
I was merely going to suggest

51:25.541 --> 51:27.726
that perhaps your luck might change,

51:27.750 --> 51:29.350
shall we say double of things.

51:32.500 --> 51:38.517
(laughing)

51:38.541 --> 51:43.308
(dramatic music)

52:03.083 --> 52:06.101
(yelling)

52:06.125 --> 52:10.891
Light up, light up.

52:41.666 --> 52:42.517
(dramatic music)

52:42.541 --> 52:43.683
Lay, lay.

52:44.416 --> 52:47.016
(horn blaring)

52:49.625 --> 52:53.891
(cheering)

53:00.000 --> 53:01.183
Emperor Katicala,

53:02.625 --> 53:03.725
Emperor Gator,

53:05.041 --> 53:07.350
citizens of Rome.

53:09.250 --> 53:15.391
These sacred games are
held to honor the victory of Rome

53:15.875 --> 53:18.558
over the barbarians of Numidia.

53:18.833 --> 53:24.850
(yelling)

53:25.375 --> 53:28.225
And honor Rome's legionary commander,

53:29.041 --> 53:31.141
General Eustace Acacius.

53:31.416 --> 53:33.933
(cheering)

53:34.208 --> 53:36.475
And with him, Lucilla,

53:37.250 --> 53:40.141
the daughter of Emperor Marcus Aurelius.

53:41.541 --> 53:44.850
(cheering)

53:46.750 --> 53:47.750
Acacius.

53:48.583 --> 53:49.583
General.

53:50.625 --> 53:58.350
(cheering)

53:59.000 --> 54:07.250
Speak to them.

54:07.833 --> 54:10.016
(cheering)

54:18.625 --> 54:22.183
I am not an orator or a politician.

54:24.250 --> 54:25.250
I am a soldier.

54:28.708 --> 54:32.683
I've seen bravery in
men and women during war,

54:34.291 --> 54:35.516
and even once in this arena.

54:37.333 --> 54:39.225
So if you ask anything of the gods,

54:41.250 --> 54:42.683
ask for that same bravery.

54:42.958 --> 54:45.350
(dramatic music)

54:45.875 --> 54:47.225
Because Rome needs it now.

54:48.291 --> 54:51.058
(cheering)

55:10.333 --> 55:11.101
(cheering)

55:11.125 --> 55:12.350
From the South Gate,

55:13.458 --> 55:17.475
bakers from the
stable of Matronos of Vistrus.

55:26.791 --> 55:30.183
(cheering)

55:30.708 --> 55:36.058
From the stables of
Emperors Calicalla and Gator themselves,

55:36.875 --> 55:41.266
the undefeated
champion, Glissero the Destroyer.

55:43.166 --> 55:45.058
(explosions)

55:45.250 --> 55:50.351
(dramatic music)

55:50.375 --> 55:51.375
Oh!

55:52.916 --> 56:01.666
(cheering)

